COLLEGE FOOTBALL REPORT; 
</P>
<P>
WEEKDAY UPDATE; 
</P>
<P>
UCLA; 
</P>
<P>
OFFENSE FINDS HAPPY MEDIUM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Football coaches usually strive for a balanced offense, but UCLA had to use its 
passing game more often early in the season because it fell behind against 
Oklahoma, Stanford and Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
However, in victories over Washington State and San Diego State and a loss to 
Arizona, the Bruins have rushed for 680 yards and passed for 681 yards. 
</P>
<P>
Tailback Brian Brown has rushed for 100 or more yards in each of the past three 
games. For the season, he has gained 425 yards, a 4.8-yard average. Fullback 
Kevin Smith has gained 305 yards, a 4.6 average. MAL FLORENCE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA AT LOS ANGELES; COLLEGE ATHLETICS; FOOTBALL TEAMS; 
FOOTBALL PLAYERS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA101690-0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 292951 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 16, 1990, Tuesday, Home Edition 
