<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: MOVIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A New Identity for Costner: The Sioux Nation has decided to make Kevin Costner 
an adopted member of the tribe in appreciation of his sensitive portrayal of 
the Sioux people as director and star of the film, "Dances With Wolves," due 
out in theaters Nov. 9. 
</P>
<P>
The Sioux nation will adopt Costner as a brother of Sinte Gleska College, the 
place where Costner and his crew were given a crash course in Lakota, the Sioux 
language. About 30% of the movie is in Lakota, with subtitles. Costner and 
co-producer Jim Wilson and co-star Mary McDonnell will all be adopted in a 
ceremony in Washington on Friday . CLAUDIA PUIG 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Costner 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
