<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA ANA OKS ORDINANCE TO LIMIT GARAGE SALES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LILY ENG, TIMES STAFF WRITER. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SANTA ANA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The City Council approved an ordinance Monday night that would limit households 
to two garage sales a year. 
</P>
<P>
In a unanimous vote, the council agreed to regulate garage sales in the city 
and drop a 1960 law, which had previously prohibited all types of sales from 
residential households. 
</P>
<P>
Despite the 1960 law, City Manager David N. Ream said, garage sales have 
thrived in Santa Ana. City officials say garage sales have gone slightly awry 
in neighborhoods where some residents have been illegally using their garages 
as retail outlets. 
</P>
<P>
Merchandise -- some of which is stolen or was just recently purchased from 
local thrift and outlet stores -- have been sold for profits in these 
garage-type businesses, city officials said. 
</P>
<P>
The new law prohibits these businesses from operating, Ream said. And the 
ordinance would also mandate that only household items can be sold. 
</P>
<P>
In a staff report to the City Council, Planning Department staff member Steve 
Crawford describes garage sales as being "part of the American experience." 
</P>
<P>
The report says that garage sales have positive benefits for Santa Ana, 
including giving residents a chance to "spring clean" and help the environment 
at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
"From an environmental standpoint, a garage sale provides the vehicle wherein 
the life of durable goods is extended, rather than the goods being relegated to 
a landfill," the report says. 
</P>
<P>
The new law will limit the hours of a garage sale from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. and to 
no more than three consecutive days. Households also cannot conduct the sales 
onpublic sidewalks, parkways, or alleys. And displays for the garage sales 
cannot be posted on telephone poles, street lights or traffic signs. 
</P>
<P>
In Ventura County, a Moorpark city ordinance limits garage and home boutique 
sales to three a year and prohibits residents' displaying sale items on front 
lawns. Moorpark adopted the ordinance after residents complained that signs to 
advertise home boutique sales littered lawns during the holiday season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
